{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox Italian comune | name = Montecarlo | official_name = Comune di Montecarlo | native_name = | image_skyline = Montecarlo_Panorama.JPG | imagesize = | image_alt = | image_caption = | image_shield = | shield_alt = | image_map = | map_alt = | map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|43|51|05|N|10|40|04|E|type:city(4,450)_region:IT|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_footnotes = | region = [[Tuscany]] | province = [[Province of Lucca|Lucca]] (LU) | frazioni = San Giuseppe, San Piero in Campo, San Salvatore, Turchetto | mayor_party = | mayor = Vittorio Fantozzi | area_footnotes = | area_total_km2 = 15.67 | population_footnotes = <ref name="istat">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref> | population_total = 4397 | population_as_of = 31 March 2017 | pop_density_footnotes = | population_demonym = Montecarlesi | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 162 | twin1 = | twin1_country = | saint = | day = | postal_code = 55015 | area_code = 0583 | website = {{official website|http://www.comune.montecarlo.lu.it/}} | footnotes = }} [[File:Castellomontecarlo.JPG|thumb|right|Castle (''Rocca del Cerruglio'') of Montecarlo.]] '''Montecarlo''' is a ''[[comune]]'' (municipality) in the [[Province of Lucca]] in the Italian region [[Tuscany]], located about {{convert|50|km|mi}} west of [[Florence]] and about {{convert|12|km|mi|0}} east of [[Lucca]].
==History== Fort and village Montecarlo was founded in 1333 by future Bohemian king and Holy Roman Emperor [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]] (Montecarlo in Italian means "Charles' Mountain"), who freed the nearby city of Lucca from the [[Republic of Pisa|Pisan]] rule. A true settlement, however, appeared only after the [[Republic of Florence|Florentine]]s destroyed the nearby castle of Vivinaia, and the authorities of the [[Republic of Lucca]] moved the population to the same hill of Charles' castle.
Montecarlo was a possession of the Republic of Florence from 1437.
==Main sights== *[[Sant'Andrea, Montecarlo (Tuscany)|Sant'Andrea]]- Collegiate church first built in the 14th century, but much of the structure, including the interior, was refurbished in 1783. It is the tallest building in the village. The crypt retains the [[Romanesque architecture]]. *[[San Piero in Campo, Montecarlo (Tuscany)|San Piero in Campo]]- Pieve or ''rural parish church'' at the foot of Montecarlo's castle. The building, among the first mentioned in Early Medieval Lucchese documents, has one of the oldest bell towers in the whole diocese of [[Lucca]]. The church was completely rebuilt in the 12th century and again after the village was destroyed in the 14th century. *''Rocca del Cerruglio'' *''Teatro dei Rassicurati''
==Twin towns== Montecarlo is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:
* {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Karlštejn (Beroun District)|Karlštejn]], Czech Republic, since 2002 * {{flagicon|France}} [[Althen-des-Paluds]], France, since 2003 * {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Mylau]], Germany, since 2006
